Iâ€™m truly humbled by the overwhelming response to this videoâ€”thank you all for watching, sharing, and caring deeply about these issues. I wanted to address some of the most common comments:

1)To those asking about my safety: Thank you for your concern! Iâ€™m completely safe. â˜º Many of the issues discussed in this video are already openly debated on Chinese social media, and I actually drew a lot of insights from those discussions while making this video.

2) Will there be more investigations like this? Honestly, Iâ€™m not sure. While I believe in shedding light on these topics, I also recognize that labor conditions in global manufacturingâ€”not just at Sheinâ€”are deeply tied to complex supply and demand forces. Real change takes time.

3)To those rethinking their shopping habits: It means so much to hear that this video has made some of you more aware. If thereâ€™s one takeaway, itâ€™s that ALL fast fashionâ€”not just Sheinâ€”often relies on labor conditions that may be far worse than what most consumers realize.

Again, thank you for engaging with this discussion so thoughtfully. Your comments have given me a lot to reflect on!ğŸ™‚

comment: I feel like the album is titled blonde because blonde hair is often bright when one is young, but it begins to darken as they age. I feel like this is used to discuss how we lose our freedom with age. After the nights beat switch, the album takes a darker tone. In the first half of the album (before nights) frank uses high-pitched vocals to represent his younger self. he also mentions the word summer several times in this album which usually represent youth and freedom. In the second half of the album (after the nights beat switch) he only references summer once when Andre 3000 says he is â€œwatching the summer come close to an endâ€ which sounds like a representation of the end of his childhood.

comment: This song sounds like new to me - the start of summer, the start of a new love, the start of nothing, so to speak. It has a somber, nostalgic tone to it - you can tell this is a song about looking back, not about living. Through the album, the new feeling (especially in the context of 4 years waiting for an album) tells the beginning, middle, and end of a time in your life. That's what makes it so relatable - we all have our lived experience, which we link intrinsically with the first half of Blonde, and the second half grounds us to our lives now. It's one of the realest, most evocative albums ever

title: If you think fast fashion is bad, check out SHEIN

Everyone around me buys Shein. Now, I do understand the fact that why go spend more when you can spend less. And it is true that not everybody can afford better brands and that almost all brands work like this nowadays. Honestly the reason I never gave in to Shein or other stuff is because they also steal artists work. I mostly thrift my clothes, or don't buy at all. If I have to, I stay in between my budget by trying to polluting less. My advices especially to young people are:
- don't buy what you don't really need
- don't buy what you don't really like
- buy what lasts
- buy versatile, basic essentials clothing to mix and match
- only splurge once in a while and try to make it a good sustainable one
- swap clothes w friends, relatives etc or thrift them
- ignore the urge to mass buy you don't need that many clothes

comment:
Nike, listen up! Here is what you need to focus on: The customer! 
I buy several pairs of running shoes every year. I will only buy in a brick-and-mortar store after trying them on because I am slightly older and only shoes with a great fit and the right amount of cushioning and stability will enable me to run and walk safely and pain free. Despite living in a reasonably large city (300K residents) I have in recent years not been able to lay my hands on any of your more premium offerings. I am not talking about the lifestyle/fashion stuff here. I have several sports retailers available, but they only carry very limited supplies of Nike, at best one or two of the models that would be of interest to me, and my size, which is very common, is almost always out of stock. I know that Nike makes some great shoes, but I would have to travel hundreds of miles to find a store with a full selection. So my money has gone to Brooks, Asics and Hoka, despite having a lot of respect for Nike.
title: How Nikeâ€™s New CEO Plans To Turn Things Around

comment: Part of the problem is that the hype surrounding Nike and Jordan products has fizzled out. The company raised prices, flooded the market with too many releases, oversaturated retro models, and failed to deliver major new innovations. This combination killed much of the resale market by overproducing product and eliminating scarcity. At the same time, the cost of living has skyrocketed, and the core consumer base between the ages of 15 and 40 has been hit hardest by these changes. A significant portion of that group is also aging out of the brand, which makes Nikeâ€™s drop in popularity easier to understand.
title: How Nikeâ€™s New CEO Plans To Turn Things Around
